<paragraph blockId="13.[1009,1259,1778,1836]" box="[1009,1259,1778,1804]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">
<taxonomicName box="[1009,1188,1778,1804]" genus="Ionoscopiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="694" rank="genus">Ionoscopiformes</taxonomicName>
indet.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1009,1259,1778,1836]" box="[1071,1196,1810,1836]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">
(
<figureCitation box="[1080,1142,1810,1836]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[132,143,1265,1282]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetId="figure-294@13.[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Actinopterygian remains from the Berriasian of Angeac-Charente:A, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-39); B, C, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-110); D, dentulous vomerine element of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-56); E-G, isolated tooth of Ionoscopiformes indet. (ANG M-111); H, jaw frag- ment of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-38) in lingual view; I, vertebra of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-069). Scale bar: A-C, E-H, 500 µm; D, 250 µm; I, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902051/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
E-G)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[813,1457,1874,2028]" box="[813,957,1874,1900]" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[813,1457,1874,2028]" lastBlockId="14.[130,776,215,369]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="695" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">
Small, curved teeth with a pointed apex bearing two short, blunt carinae are assigned to an indeterminate ionoscopiform (
<figureCitation box="[821,881,1969,1995]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[132,143,1265,1282]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetId="figure-294@13.[132,1455,215,1222]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Actinopterygian remains from the Berriasian of Angeac-Charente:A, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-39); B, C, isolated tooth of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-110); D, dentulous vomerine element of Amiiformes indet. (ANG M-56); E-G, isolated tooth of Ionoscopiformes indet. (ANG M-111); H, jaw frag- ment of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-38) in lingual view; I, vertebra of Actinopterygii indet. (ANG M-069). Scale bar: A-C, E-H, 500 µm; D, 250 µm; I, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902051/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="694">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
E-G). Small ganoid scales characterized by a finely serrated posterior margin may also belong to this group. Such a material is similar to that described from the Purbeckian beds of Chassiron (Vullo 
<emphasis box="[307,354,247,273]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">et al.</emphasis>
2014). As some recent studies suggest that Ionoscopiformes is not a monophyletic clade (
<bibRefCitation author="EBERT M." box="[583,694,279,305]" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" pagination="1420071" refId="ref38761" refString="EBERT M. 2018. - Cerinichthys koelblae, gen. et sp. nov., from the Upper Jurassic of Cerin, France, and its phylogenetic setting, leading to a reassessment of the phylogenetic relationships of Halecomorphi (Actinopterygii). Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 38 (1): e 1420071. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 027 24634.2017. 1420071" type="journal article" year="2018">Ebert2018</bibRefCitation>
;López- 
<bibRefCitation author="ARBARELLO A. &amp; SFERCO E." box="[132,386,311,337]" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" pagination="172337" refId="ref42573" refString="LOPEZ- ARBARELLO A. &amp; SFERCO E. 2018. - Neopterygian phylogeny: the merger assay. Royal Society Open Science 5: 172337. https: // doi. org / 10.1098 / rsos. 172337" type="journal article" year="2018">Arbarello &amp; Sferco 2018</bibRefCitation>
), the material from Angeac-Charente is assigned to Ionoscopiformes 
<emphasis box="[451,501,344,369]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="GRANDE L. &amp; BEMIS W. E." box="[508,765,343,369]" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" pagination="1 - 696" refId="ref40685" refString="GRANDE L. &amp; BEMIS W. E. 1998. - A comprehensive phylogenetic study of amiid fishes (Amiidae) based on comparative skeletal anatomy. An empirical search for interconnected patterns of natural history. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 18 (suppl. 1): 1 - 696." type="journal article" year="1998">Grande &amp; Bemis (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
